definitions.example: It finally came out that he had been lying all the time.
My new book comes out next week.

definitions.definition: (old-fashioned or historical) (as a debutante) To make a formal debut in society.

definitions.example: There were a lot of problems at the start, but it all came out well in the end.

definitions.definition: (of a batsman) To walk onto the field at the beginning of an innings.
To come out of the closet.
definitions.example: He came out to his parents as gay last week.
That comes out of my paycheck.
You had come out in favor of the French Revolution.

definitions.definition: (of the sun, moon or stars) To become visible in the sky as a result of clouds clearing away.
definitions.example: It's quite warm now the sun's come out.

definitions.definition: To go on strike, especially out of solidarity with other workers.
definitions.example: We got the folks at the Detroit plant to come out too.

definitions.definition: To make a debut in a new field.
